As a gift for my neighbour I bought a mass-produced Ikea LAMPAN lamp and made it personal by adding some relevant text to the top of the lampshade.
The effect of the text on the top of the lamp cannot be seen on the ceiling but it's clearly visible.

1) Get a LAMPAN from Ikea (art.nr. 200.469.88; â‚¬2,99 each in the Netherlands 2012). Red, white and black versions are available. You'll only need the bottom part of the lamp. 2) Change the text in the lampshade to your personal liking. You can also remove text and print a simple version. 3) Open the STL with modified text in slicer and place the lampshade upside down on the build platform. Choose some extra bottom layers (I choose 6 bottom layers @0,3mm) to get some extra contrast in the text. 4) Choose a nice material (color + opacity). I suggest using materials with low transparancies since the effect of the text will be better. 5) Print 6) Put in on the LAMPAN base 7) Enjoy! To improve the effect of the lampshade you can change wall thickness to make more or less light get through. This can also be done with the bottom thickness. It depends on the chosen color + tranparancy really. ATTENTION: be aware that the bulb inside the LAMPAN can get hot. NOTES:
You'll need a relatively big build volume to print this 1:1. It'll fit an Ultimaker.
The STL is drawn quiet 'large' in order to make your print fit the LAMPAN base easily. It'll not click onto the base as the standard lampshade does.

This is an attachment for a dremel or similar tool that makes it easy to grind tungsten electrodes for TIG welding. It has holes for 1/16", 3/32" and 1/8" electrodes at 4 different angles. It uses a diamond disc that I got at harbor freight (I think) Thanks to Lenbok ( http://www.thingiverse.com/Lenbok ) for the original design. I'd been meaning to design this for a while but his design did most of the work for me.

Print it out. There are now two versions of the file, one is a little larger than the other to fit a 45mm diameter grinding wheel. If the holes are a little small you can enlarge them either by sticking a hot electrode through them or with a drill bit. Put the diamond disc and arbor inside the attachment so that the arbor is sticking out the threaded end.
Put the arbor in the collet and tighten it and then thread the attachment onto the nose of the tool. Turn it on, put the electrode in the appropriate hole and sharpen it. Be careful that the electrode doesn't get too hot and melt the plastic.

description.text:
This was designed, along with my father, to hold a piece of wood for turning on a lathe. The idea is to turn a handle and a sphere initially. The sphere will then be mounted into the center of this chuck and held in place with M4x70 bolts and nuts, tightened to grip, with the handle emerging through one of the side cuts. Once mounted onto the lathe using a grip chuck, the sphere can be cut in half and turned out to form a bowl.

Ideally, this should be printed in a strong material, such as PETG, which will allow some sort of give to aid gripping. The chuck is designed to fit a roughly 44mm diameter sphere. A larger chuck could be create for larger jobs fairly easily. I printed this in E3D Edge, and am looking forward to hearing from my father how well this experiment works.

Update: 20th Dec 2017. Finally got around to testing this out with my Dad yesterday. I've switched the 'Work In Progress' flag on as the part failed during initial testing. However, this has therefore allowed me to tweak the design a little and I'll be able to test the re-design again next week. The part broke in two ways: the first break was probably the result of not being aware of the forces the part would undergo; the initial spinup of the part creates a huge shearing force which began to rip the the base (held in the metal chuck jaw) away from the main model. Strength can be improved here by printing 3 solid diaphragm layers each side of the boundary. The second break came from overtightening, which then began to cause delamination at the base of the four corner towers. I'll be prinitng this in flexible material (or maybe ultimately a mix of flexible and other) to prevent this issue from recurring.

If you can obtain M4 threaded rod, the knurled nuts are here to simplifying the process of tightening the chuck around the spoon blank.

Notes:

Print upside down.
The holder part is designed to support the underside of the spoon's globe. You may find it necessary to cut it's height by a few mm by pushing it below the surface of the printing bed in your slicing software.

description.text:
This design supercedes http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1801124, and has been created for use in conjunction with http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1792366, which purpose is to strengthen the frame of the Prusa i3 Pro B. I refrained from the temptation to design this free of metal ball bearings and other non-printable parts, like the metal rods, as I'm stepping on these kind of materials here, given my collector's nature of everything seemingly or potentially useful. I'm happy that 3D-printing enables me to give some of those materials a purpose again, so it would be counterproductive to go for lengths to work around their actual reuse.
Anyway, steel ball bearings with metal rods are sound and solid, and work well with this application.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa i3 Pro B cheap China clone

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3mm/layer, 0.4mm nozzle

15% 3dhoneycomb

Notes:

These print easily - but you may want to verify proper 1st layer, as there are 4 parts in the placement.
Filament use is moderate: from a 1 kg reel of material, about 80 sets can be printed.

The barrels the reel is rolling on are relatively close together - I still have to observe whether this imposes a problem in case of filament tangle, which could pull the reel down. Spacing is such because this way, reel mass rests entirely on the support rods, but I'm considering to add a configuration item for spacing the bearings.

Bill of material:
  • 4 ball bearings, about any reasonable size will do (customiser). Presets are for 6x10x3 bearings (MR106ZZ).
  • 2 pieces of rod or pipe, fitting into the above bearings. Lengths a bit more than widest reels you're using. Reels will rest and roll on these. Widest reels I have are 88mm wide. From the used 2mm wall strength 6mm outer diameter aluminium pipe I cut two 96mm long pieces.
  • 8 bolts M3, 10mm (more or less depending on configuration item "wall"), 8 nuts, also M3, and 8 or 16 washers.
  • Printed parts of this design.
  • A Prusa I3 (or other), modified (or standard) with two horizontal rods at top, to which this stand can be clamped to.

For printable modification parts for the i3, refer to http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1792366

Afterthought: It may have been easier to simply push four U-groove ball bearings with internal diameter of the rods onto those very same rods, and let the reel run on those.
But those seem to be hard to get - most I've seen feature an inner diameter of 4mm, to small for the used rods. Cylindric bearings with guards added both sides may be an alternative.

I'm considering to augment this design with a mount point for a bowden extruder, while raising the bearings, and therefore the reel rest.
